Takeaways

  • Fifty-nine percent more Los Angeles County motorcyclists lost their lives in 2012 than in 2010 as motorcycle fatalies outpaced vehicle registrations, according to the most recent data available through the Statewide Integrated Traffic Records System(SWITRS) and the California Department of Motor Vehicles.

  • Over that same time period, total vehicle registrations increased by two percent.

  • This increase in fatalities follows a general pattern in Los Angeles County since 2003 in which motorcycle fatalies decline before again increasing.

  • The most recent decline - about 36 percent - came between 2008 (111 fatalities) and 2010 (71 fatalities). This followed an increase of about 28.8 percent between 2003 and 2008, according to SWITRS data.

  • Across the state, the increase between 2010 and 2012 was about 29.6 percent, while the decrease between 2008 and 2010 was 34.2 percent.

  • Orange County followed a similar pattern. Motorcyclist fatalities dropped 39.4 percent between 2008 and 2010 but increased 15 percent between 2010 and 2012, according to SWITRS data. Between 2003 and 2008 motorcycle fatalities in Orange County increased 57.1 percent.

  • Statewide, 3.8 percent of collisions involving motorcycles in 2012 led to at least one fatality. In comparison, about 1.7 percent of collisions that don’t involve motorcycles in 2012 led to at least one fatality.

  • Between 2003 and 2012 non-motorcycle collisions declined about 24 percent, dropping from 198,277 collisions to 150,837 collisions, according to the data.

  • The trend in Los Angeles County was similar, though the decline was about 19 percent, from 59,010 collisions to 47,858 collsions, according to the data.

  • Overall in the state collisions involving motorcycles have increased 21 percent since 2003.
    • Statewide there was a general increase between 2003 and 2009 before declining to near-2003 levels, according to the data. However since 2010 collisions involving motorcycles have shown an increase of about 16 percent, according to the data.
  • Overall in Los Angeles County, collisions involving motorcycles have increased 49 percent since 2003. The county showed a similar pattern to the state though the years of the decreases and increases were different.
    • The number of collsions involving motorcyles in 2005 was 11 percent lower than in 2003.
    • This was followed by an increase to 3,048 collisions involving motorcyles in 2008, a 52 percent increase.
    • Declines came in 2009 and 2010 followed by increases in 2011 and 2012.

  • In LA County there have been two sizable dips in the rate of fatalities per 100,000 registered motorcycles: from 2003 to 2007. Fatalities increased again in 2008 before dipping. 2012 saw another increase.

  • Year over year, the most frequent type of collision involving motorcycles in Los Angeles County are broadside collisions. This kind of collision has increased about 56 percent between 2003 and 2012. Why might this be?

  • Sideswipe collisions are the fourth leading kind of collision that leads to fatalities, behind broadside, hit object and rear-end collisions.

  • About the data:

    • We downloaded Statewide Integrated Traffic Records System (SWITRS) data from the University of California-Berkley through its Transportation Injury Mapping System.

      • The data contains collisions reported to CHP from local and governmental agencies between 2003 and 2012.

    • Collisions without motorcycles

      • Queried the data for those collisions in which the identifier for whether it was a motorcycle collision mccol was NULL or blank.

    • Collisions with motorcycles

      • Queried the data for those collisions in which the identifier for whether it was a motorcycle collision mccol was Y.

    • Motorcyclists killed in collisions

      • Queried the data for those collisions in which the identifier for whether it was a motorcycle collision (mccol) was Y and getting the SUM of the mckill column.

    • Motorcyclists injured in collisions

      • Queried the data for those collisions in which the identifier for whether it was a motorcycle collision (mccol) was Y and getting the SUM of the mcinjure column.

    • Fatal collisions all

      • Queried the data to find those collisions in which the crashsev equaled 1

    • Fatal collisions involving motorcyclists

      • Queried the data for whether it was a motorcycle collision (mccol) was Y and mckill was greater than zero.
